3) Training Helper Class¶

In [6]:
class Trainer():
    '''Helper class to train neural network models'''
        # TODO explain arguments
        
    def __init__(
        self,
        net, 
        train_data, val_data,
        batch_size, lr=0.01, lr_decay_every=10,
        l2_norm = 0,
        save_path="results/",
        device="cpu"):
        
        self.net = net
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.lr = lr
        
        self.save_path = save_path
        # clear output folder contents if it already exists
        if os.path.exists(self.save_path): 
            os.system("rm -rf "+self.save_path)
        os.makedirs(self.save_path)
        
        # initialize the data loaders for training and validation
        self.train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
            train_data, batch_size=self.batch_size, shuffle=True, num_workers=8)
        self.val_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
            val_data, batch_size=self.batch_size, num_workers=8)
        
        # ADAM optimizer with L2_norm regularization option
        self.optimizer = optim.Adam(self.net.parameters(), lr=self.lr, weight_decay=l2_norm)
        # learning rate scheduler: reduces by 10% every 'lr_decay_every' epochs
        self.scheduler = optim.lr_scheduler.LambdaLR(self.optimizer, 
                                lambda e : (1-(0.1)*(e//lr_decay_every)) if (e//lr_decay_every)<10 else 0.1)
        
        #states that track loss, accuracy etc. Set some dummy values for epoch 0
        states_dict = OrderedDict([ 
             ("epoch duration",[0]), ("loss",[0.01]), ("val_loss",[0.01]),
             ("accuracy",[0.0]), ("val_accuracy",[0.0])
            ])
        self.results = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(states_dict)        
        self.results.index.name = "epoch"
        self.n = 0
        
        
    def train(self):
        
        self.start_time = time.time()
        self.n += 1 # a count of how many times train() is called
        
        train_loss=0
        train_acc=0
        train_n=0
        # train from training split
        for images, labels in self.train_loader:
            images = images.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            preds = self.net(images)
            # calculate the loss using cross_entropy
            loss = F.cross_entropy(preds, labels)
            # back propagate the loss
            self.optimizer.zero_grad()
            loss.backward()
            # clip gradients to avoid exploding gradients
            clip_grad_value_(self.net.parameters(), 0.1)
            self.optimizer.step()

            train_loss =+ loss.item()
            train_acc =+ self.equals(preds, labels)
            train_n =+ len(images)

        self.net.eval()
        val_loss=0
        val_acc=0
        val_n=0
        
        with torch.no_grad():
            for images, labels in self.val_loader:
                images = images.to(device)
                labels = labels.to(device)
                preds = self.net(images)
                val_loss = F.cross_entropy(preds, labels)
      
                val_loss =+ val_loss.item()
                val_acc =+ self.equals(preds, labels)
                val_n =+ len(images)
        
        self.scheduler.step()
        epoch_duration = time.time() - self.start_time

        # calculate all the scores at the end of an epoch and store it
        result = OrderedDict()
        result["epoch duration"] = epoch_duration
        result["loss"] = train_loss/train_n
        result["val_loss"] = val_loss/val_n
        result["accuracy"] = round(100*train_acc/train_n,2) # in percentage 
        result["val_accuracy"] = round(100*val_acc/val_n,2) # in percentage
        self.results.loc[self.n] = result
        
        self.net.train()
        
    def end(self):
        # save training history
        self.results.to_csv(self.save_path+"results.csv")
        # plot and save the training curves
        self.plot_training_curves()
        plt.savefig(self.save_path+"training_curve.png")
        plt.suptitle(self.save_path.replace("/"," "))
        plt.show()
        # save the final model
        self.save_model("model-epoch{}".format(self.n))
        
    def save_model(self, fname="model"):
        # save model state to the path
        torch.save(self.net, self.save_path+fname+".pt")
        
    def load_model(self, path):
        # load a previously trained model from the path
        self.net.load_state_dict(path)
    
    def plot_training_curves(self):
        fig, (ax0, ax1) = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=(12,4))
        # adhoc fix my clipping loss values to avoid a distorted graph when one epoch loss is abnormally high
        self.results.loss[self.results.loss>0.01] = 0.01
        self.results.val_loss[self.results.val_loss>0.01] = 0.01
        self.results.plot(y=['loss','val_loss'], title="loss", grid=True, ax=ax0)
        self.results.plot(
            y=['accuracy','val_accuracy'], title="Classification accuracy (%)",
            grid=True, ylim=[0,100], ax=ax1)
        
    def equals(self, preds, labels):
        count = preds.argmax(dim=1).eq(labels).sum().item()
        return count

4) Architecture¶

### A Fully-convolutional network (FCN) with Batch-Norm and ELU activations. Design Decision : _FCNs have only covolutional layers instead of fully-connected layers in the end of the network (like AlexNet). A FCN (https://arxiv.org/abs/1411.4038) is chosen over a traditional CNN because they can be dynamically configurable for changing image sizes while being mathematically equivalent to traditional CNN._ Design Decision : _Each layer of the network comprises of 2 blocks of **Convolution-BatchNorm-ELU**. The first block uses same-padding while the second has zero-padding for convinience of model design._ Design Decision : _The Elu() activation is used instead of the popular ReLu activation since it is more capable of handling vanishing gradient problems while having comparable performance to ReLu_ The architectures can be further visualized in later cells of the notebook where this class is initialized.
In [7]:
class FCN(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, in_shape=(1,28,28), out_classes=10,
                 kernel_size=3, convs=[6,12], dropout=0, 
                 debug_print=False):
        
        # TODO explain args
        super().__init__()
        
        in_chns, in_h, in_w = in_shape
        self.out_classes = out_classes
        self.k = kernel_size
        assert self.k%2==1, "kernel_size must be odd numbers like 3,5,7 for this architecture to dynamically be configured."
        self.debug_print = debug_print
        self.dropout = dropout
        
        # build the convolutional layers
        self.convs = nn.ModuleList([])
        out_h, out_w = (in_h, in_w)
        
        for cin, cout in zip([in_chns]+convs, convs):
            layers = []
            # add dropout layer if requested
            if self.dropout : layers.append(nn.Dropout2d(p=dropout))
                
            # add 2 convolution layer with provided kernel_size , batch Norm and ELU activations
            # number of intermediary channels calculated dynamically
            cmid = cin + (cout-cin)//2
            layers.extend([nn.Conv2d(cin, cmid, kernel_size=self.k, padding=(self.k-1)//2), # full padding
                           nn.BatchNorm2d(cmid),
                           nn.ELU(),
                           nn.Conv2d(cmid, cout, kernel_size=self.k, padding=0), # zero padding
                           nn.BatchNorm2d(cout),
                           nn.ELU()
                          ])
            
            self.convs.append(nn.Sequential(*layers))
            # dynamically calculate the output shape of convolutions + pooling (without padding)
            # equations taken from https://medium.com/mlreview/a-guide-to-receptive-field-arithmetic-for-convolutional-neural-networks-e0f514068807
            out_h = (out_h-self.k+1)//2
            out_w = (out_w-self.k+1)//2
            if self.debug_print: print((out_h,out_w))
            assert out_h > 0 and out_w > 0
            
        # set the last FCN layer kernel_size such that it produces a single output prediction
        self.finalconv = nn.Conv2d(convs[-1], self.out_classes, kernel_size=(out_h,out_w))

        
    def forward(self, t):
        
        # loop over all convolution layers
        for i,conv in enumerate(self.convs):
            
            # 2 X covolution + non-linear Elu operation
            t = conv(t)
            if self.debug_print: print("conv{}>{}".format(i,list(t.shape)))
                
            # perform maxpool with (2x2) kernels
            t = F.max_pool2d(t, kernel_size=2, stride=2)
            if self.debug_print: print("pool{}>{}".format(i,list(t.shape)))
                
        # final layer
        t = self.finalconv(t)
        
        # no activations in the last layer since we use cross_entropy_loss with logits
        t = t.reshape(-1,self.out_classes)
        
        if self.debug_print: 
            print("final{}>{}".format(i,list(t.shape)))
            self.debug_print = False        
            
        return t

# helper function that counts the parameters in a model
def count_parameters(model):
    return sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters() if p.requires_grad)

# helper function that randomly inits the weights of the model
def init_weights(m):
    if isinstance(m, torch.nn.Conv2d) or isinstance(m, torch.nn.Linear):
        torch.nn.init.xavier_uniform_(m.weight)
        if hasattr(m, "bias") and m.bias is not None:
            torch.nn.init.zeros_(m.bias)

Design decision: _The Early stopping mechanism is implemented to keep a check on over-fitting_ _To design my early stopping algorithm, I use the analysis of Lutz Prechelt(http://page.mi.fu-berlin.de/prechelt/Biblio/stop_tricks1997.pdf). I set the stopping criteria as a moving-average of validation accuracy in the last 2 epochs to avoid stopping because of jitters in learning curve.
In [12]:
best_val_acc = 0
best_epoch = 0
patience = 0

for epoch in range(epochs):
    # train the model
    trainer.train()
        
    # display the results so far on iPython console 
    clear_output(wait=True)
    display(trainer.results)
    
    # create a model checkpoint if needed
    cur_val_acc = trainer.results.val_accuracy.iloc[-2:].mean()
    if  cur_val_acc > best_val_acc:
        best_epoch = epoch
        best_val_acc = cur_val_acc
        trainer.save_model("model_best")
        # reset patience
        patience = 0 
    else:
        patience += 1
        
    # early stop if the validation accuracy didnt improve for 5 epochs
    if patience > max_patience: 
        break

print("Stopping at epoch {}. \nBest validation accuracy = {}%".format(
    best_epoch, best_val_acc))
# at the end plot training curves, save results and model to files
trainer.end()

    root = './data/FashionMNIST',
    train = True,
    transform = transforms.Compose([
        transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(p=0.5),
        transforms.RandomVerticalFlip(p=0.2),

## Analysis of Model 1 (data augumentation) As observed from the training curve above, the added data augumentations result in a drop in the training accuracy. However, the validation accuracy and hence the generalization of the network improves. **Therefore, data augumentation is beneficial and retained for the next experiments**

# train the model variations
for name, model in model_2s.items():
    # init the trainer helper class and reset the model_weights
    model = model.apply(init_weights)
    trainer = Trainer(model, train_set, val_set,
                      batch_size=batch_size, lr=lr, lr_decay_every=lr_decay_every,
                      save_path="results-{}/".format(name),
                      device=device)
    # train   
    print("------------------------------\nTraining {} ({} parameters)\n----------------------------".format(
        name.upper(), count_parameters(model)))
    best_val_acc = 0
    best_epoch = 0
    patience = 0
    for epoch in range(epochs):
        trainer.train()
        # create a model checkpoint if needed
        cur_val_acc = trainer.results.val_accuracy.iloc[-2:].mean()
        if  cur_val_acc > best_val_acc:
            best_epoch = epoch
            best_val_acc = cur_val_acc
            trainer.save_model("model_best")
            # reset patience
            patience = 0 
        else:
            patience += 1        
        # early stop if the validation accuracy didnt improve for 5 epochs
        if patience > max_patience: 
            break
    
    model_scores.update({
        name:{
         "accuracy":best_val_acc,
         "parameters":count_parameters(model),
         "latency":trainer.results["epoch duration"].mean(),
        }})
    
    print("Stopping at epoch {}. \nBest validation accuracy = {}%".format(
        best_epoch, best_val_acc))
    # at the end plot training curves, save results and model to files
    trainer.end()

In [22]:
# increasing the patience since models with dropout and regularizers converge much slowly
max_patience=30 

# train the models with different L2-norm rates and dropout
for v, l2_norm, dropout in [("a", 0, 0.05), ("b", 0, 0.1), ("c", 1e-4, 0.05),("d", 1e-3, 0.)]:
    
    # init the model with the dropout
    name = "model_3"+v
    model = FCN(dropout=dropout, **best_model_params).to(device)
    model = model.apply(init_weights)
    
    # init the trainer helper class
    trainer = Trainer(model, train_set, val_set,
                      batch_size=batch_size, lr=lr, lr_decay_every=lr_decay_every,
                      l2_norm=l2_norm,
                      save_path="results-model_3{}/".format(v),
                      device=device)
    # train   
    print("-------------------------------\nTraining {} with L2-norm = {} and dropout = {}%\n-------------------------------\n".format(
        name.upper(), l2_norm, dropout*100))
    best_val_acc = 0
    best_epoch = 0
    patience = 0
    for epoch in range(epochs):
        trainer.train()
        # create a model checkpoint if needed
        cur_val_acc = trainer.results.val_accuracy.iloc[-2:].mean()
        if  cur_val_acc > best_val_acc:
            best_epoch = epoch
            best_val_acc = cur_val_acc
            trainer.save_model("model_best")
            # reset patience
            patience = 0 
        else:
            patience += 1        
        # early stop if the validation accuracy didnt improve for 5 epochs
        if patience > max_patience: 
            break
    
    model_scores.update({
        name:{
         "accuracy":best_val_acc,
         "parameters":count_parameters(model),
         "latency":trainer.results["epoch duration"].mean(),
        }})
    
    print("Early stopping at epoch {}. \nBest validation accuracy = {}%".format(
        best_epoch, best_val_acc))
    # at the end plot training curves, save results and model to files
    trainer.end()

## Analysis of Model 3 (regularizations) The L2_norm regularization seems to be counter productive and leads to a ~2% drop in generalization accuracy. The dropout based networks perform almost similar. The configuration MODEL_3A with **dropout=5%** and **no L2_norm** has one of the best generalization score (moving-average validation accuracy) while the training curve for training and test data are more closer. From the training curves, it can be observed that the regularizations prevents the model from overfitting easily. Even though regularizations can be seen to slightly lower the training accuracy, they are known to improve the ability of the network to generalize better. Therefore, they are expected to improve the accuracy on the test_split.

loss=0
acc=0
n=0
# validate on validation split
with torch.no_grad():
    for images, labels in test_loader:
        images = images.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)
        preds = model(images)
        l = F.cross_entropy(preds, labels)
        
        loss =+ l.item()
        acc =+ trainer.equals(preds, labels)
        n =+ len(images)
        

loss = loss/n
acc = round(100*acc/n,2) # in percentage 
print("Final Test accuracy = {}%".format(acc))
